{
  "query": "What are the observed outcomes of transplanting or seeding organisms onto intertidal artificial structures in Australian estuaries?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across replicated and often randomized/controlled studies in Australian estuaries, transplanting oysters (and in some cases coralline algae) onto intertidal artificial structures: (a) introduced macroalgae, mobile and non-mobile invertebrates, and fish species that were absent from untreated structure surfaces (community composition); (b) produced mixed effects on combined macroalgae/invertebrate richness and/or diversity depending on site and the presence/size of grooves, small ridges or ledges; (c) increased mobile invertebrate species richness on structure surfaces; (d) did not consistently increase fish species richness, with mixed effects in some cases depending on surface grooves/ridges and site (richness/diversity); (e) yielded mixed effects on combined macroalgae/invertebrate abundance, including no increase in some cases and dependence on surface features such as grooves/ridges/ledges; (f) produced mixed effects on mobile invertebrate abundance, with one study also reporting increased non-mobile invertebrate and oyster recruit abundance and decreased barnacle abundance; (g) did not consistently increase fish abundance on or around structures, and in one study fish abundance around transplanted oysters was similar regardless of groove/ridge presence/size; (h) showed variable survival of transplanted invertebrates (including oysters) depending on species, site and surface features, with higher oyster survival in grooves than on ridges and some studies simply reporting that a proportion survived; and (i) did not increase the time fishes spent interacting with surfaces or the number of bites, though benthic fishes took more bites from surfaces with transplanted oysters than from those with oysters plus coralline algae, with these behavioral results independent of groove/ridge presence/size. [3472]",
